It’s always important to shoot free throws before, during and after your on court workouts. At the end of your workouts… get in a habit of picking a number that you must make consecutive free throws, like 10, 20, etc…. 

At the end of my training sessions yesterday, I picked 30 in a row. Today at the end of my sessions, I picked 35.  As seen here from today’s video… my routine is consistent and very simple, 2 dribbles and I always keep my shoulders relaxed so I don’t “steer” the ball.

This past Friday our Player Development Team of @nolanwillett3 @matthew_guinto @davidkap0 and myself along with 75+ of our Athletes celebrated the Willett Basketball Foundation 2 year anniversary♥️

A huge shout out to the family @257ace behind the 📸 capturing some great pics and this 🔥 reel!! Also, thank you to @edgeprepbasketball for donating court time for this special day!!

The Willett Basketball Foundation creates opportunities for the youth to get Elite Professional training to help them build skill and confidence in the sport and life.
Donations to the foundation go towards sponsoring student athletes for elite training.

The foundation holds student-athletes to a high standard on and off the court to help create leaders out of young men and women athletes in our city.  Since launching the non-profit foundation 2 years ago, we’ve already been able to provide full and partial training scholarships to over 50 athletes!! @corinnewillett and I have matched every dollar that has come in and we will continue to do so. 

The Willett Basketball Foundation is excited about the future as we continue to help level the playing field♥️ You can find the link to the foundation in BIO.

Thank you to the families and companies that have generously donated to the foundation over the past 2 years!  You are all incredible!

This 1v1 drill is great for the following reasons:
- works on players quick first step
- teaches player to cut the defender off if they beat them on the first step
- teaches player to maintain contact and their dribble if they’re hip to hip
- teaches player to play with pace if the defender beats them to the cut off spot
- works on finishing with contact

Lastly, it will help you get under the ball so you are in the correct shooting position.

For the HS seniors out there that are tuning up their on court skills and their bodies this spring/summer to prepare for their College/University freshman season…  I speak from experience as I was the only freshman that made the roster back in 1988 (I’m sitting front row on the right). The average age of my teammates were 22/23 years old and I was 18.  That first couple weeks of practices could have gone one of two ways… However, I was going to be a 100% in control of how that first couple weeks were going to go for myself as I came in mentally confident and physically prepared. That spring/summer leading up to my freshman year, I was on the court for 3 hours a day working on my game and scrimmaging against the College/University/Pro guys each day. 

There are a lot of different coaching styles out there. Our coaching staff sat back the first few weeks and let the players battle and fight it out every possession on the court.  They wanted to see what everyone was made of and who was going to fight for their position/role on the team because it sure wasn’t going to be handed to you. Yeah, on the first day one player had four front teeth knocked out and it even sometimes spilled over to the locker room as no one was going to back down from the challenge.  However, this mentality kept us competitive with each other on a daily basis and before we knew it, we were all a cohesive team and we viewed each other as family!

The season took care of itself as we went undefeated, I ended up as a starter going into the second half of the season and our team won a national championship🏆 

#ifitstobeitsuptome #noexcuses #summerofseparation

From our WHY WHAT HOW book…

Set goals: Establish short-term and long-term goals for your academics, basketball performance, and personal growth. Having clear objectives will help you stay focused and motivated.  Willett uses this analogy with his athletes… “Imagine a dart board on the wall across the entire gym. The bullseye being your longterm basketball, academic, personal goals. Willett asked the players, can you throw a dart from here across the entire gym and hit the bullseye? They always respond, of course not. He then uses that time to talk about the importance of creating short term daily, weekly and monthly attainable goals that allow you to take a small step each day towards that dart board.  Eventually, if you stick to the plan and keep checking off those short term goals, you’ll be standing in front of that board and you’ll be able to place the dart in the bullseye.” @baskettalks 

@nolanwillett3 @davidkap0 @matthew_guinto

Here is a great example of how we build progressions/stacks into our “game situation” movements📈

The initial foundation of this situation is as follows:
The player is coming off side screen action and attack outside hip of secondary defender into snatch back or under drag, then re-attacking top foot at an exaggerated angle to set up the spin.

The 3 progressions/stacks on the back end of the play goes as follows: 

Option 1) Spin and finish at the basket 
Option 2) Fake 1/2 spin into midrange jumper
Option 3) Fake 1/2 spin into pump fake up and under finish at the basket 

PS. Notice that all movements from the @yonsei_basketball athletes are done at game pace and with game energy✌️

Key points when working on stationary handles:
- chest up
- wide balanced base
- eyes forward 
- upper body relaxed 
- control breathing 
- if you’re working speed use timed intervals 
- if you’re working on control use over exaggerated movements 
- get uncomfortable and be willing to mess up

I’ve been around the world teaching this game and the rocker step (shimmy step) is one of those moves that I’m very careful of teaching in most cases.  It’s typically going to get called for a travel in Europe. I don’t see it get called much in the KBL. It’s a hit and a miss in North America at the AAU and HS level.  It typically gets called at the College level.  It never gets called in the NBA or WNBA.

To be honest… I don’t think it’s possible to do it effectively without travelling. In this video from a few years ago, we were working on 6-8 standard options off of triple threat. I threw the rocker step in at the end as a bonus. In this demonstration, I do everything I can to put the ball down before I lift my pivot foot and when I watch the video in slow motion I still lift my pivot first.  Yes, the move can happen so quickly that the ref often won’t be able to see if the ball hit first but if you get a ref that has played the game, they’re probably going to call it. 

Hoopers & Coaches out there.. what are your thoughts?

These 3 consecutive 1v1 buckets by @mj.okado_ (with a dribble limit of 3) are as textbook as you’re going to get.

Efficiency & Details:
First bucket- Sells the pump fake with an added ball and body lift to get defender to close out aggressively. This allows the player to cut into defenders body on the first dribble and then create space on the step back.
Second bucket- player had space to get the catch & shoot 3 off because defenders close out was a little more tentative because of the rep before.
Third bucket- player sets up the close out defender with connecting a pump fake into jab step before he puts the ball down. This gets the defender out of position and has him running out to block the step back.  Player sold the identical footwork, handwork, eyes, hip drop that he had shot the ball from in the first rep so this got the defender in the air.

When an elite skill set matched with a high basketball IQ comes together… it’s beautiful to watch📈
